# Sufficient dimension reduction

In [statistics](/Statistics), sufficient dimension reduction (SDR) is a paradigm for analyzing data that combines the ideas of [Dimension reduction](/Dimension_reduction) with the concept of [sufficiency](/Sufficient_statistic).  The term was coined to capture the intuition that, when faced with a high‑dimensional vector of predictors **x**, one can often extract a much smaller collection of statistics that still preserves essentially all the information relevant to the response **y**.  In practice this means that the conditional distribution of **y** given the reduced statistics is identical to the conditional distribution of **y** given the full predictor vector.  In other words, the reduction is *sufficient* if no additional knowledge about **x** improves the prediction of **y** once the reduced representation is known.  

The motivation for SDR is rooted in the observation that classical regression techniques become unwieldy — or even infeasible — when **p**, the dimension of **x**, grows large.  Early work in [regression analysis](/Regression_analysis) focused on estimating the conditional distribution of **y** given **x**, denoted **y | x**, and on summarizing that distribution in ways that are both interpretable and computationally tractable.  A *sufficient summary plot* is a graphical representation that contains exactly the same information as the full conditional distribution; when such a plot can be drawn in low dimensions, it provides a vivid visual intuition about the relationship between **y** and **x**.  

## Graphical motivation

In a regression setting, it is often useful to summarize the distribution of  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

graphically.  For instance, one may consider a [scatterplot](/Scatterplot) of **y** versus one or more of the predictors or a linear combination of the predictors.  A scatterplot that contains all available regression information is called a sufficient summary plot.  

When **x** is high‑dimensional, particularly when  

\[
p \ge 3
\]

, it becomes increasingly challenging to construct and visually interpret sufficiency summary plots without reducing the data.  Even three‑dimensional scatter plots must be viewed via a [computer program](/Computer_program), and the third dimension can only be visualized by rotating the coordinate axes.  However, if there exists a sufficient dimension reduction  

\[
R({\textbf x})
\]

with small enough dimension, a sufficient summary plot of **y** versus  

\[
R({\textbf x})
\]

may be constructed and visually interpreted with relative ease.  

Hence sufficient dimension reduction allows for graphical intuition about the distribution of  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

, which might not have otherwise been available for high‑dimensional data.  

Most graphical methodology focuses primarily on dimension reduction involving linear combinations of **x**.  The rest of this article deals only with such reductions.  

## Dimension reduction subspace

Suppose  

\[
R({\textbf x}) = A^{T}{\textbf x}
\]

is a sufficient dimension reduction, where **A** is a  

\[
p \times k
\]

[matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) with [rank](/Rank_(linear_algebra))

\[
k \le p
\]

.  Then the regression information for  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

can be inferred by studying the distribution of  

\[
y\mid A^{T}{\textbf x}
\]

, and the plot of **y** versus  

\[
A^{T}{\textbf x}
\]

is a sufficient summary plot.  

[Without loss of generality](/Without_loss_of_generality), only the [space](/Vector_space) [spanned](/Linear_span) by the columns of **A** need be considered.  Let  

\[
\eta
\]

be a [basis](/Basis_(linear_algebra)) for the [column space](/Row_and_column_spaces) of **A**, and let the space spanned by  

\[
\eta
\]

be denoted by  

\[
\mathcal{S}(\eta)
\].

It follows from the definition of a sufficient dimension reduction that  

\[
F_{y\mid x}=F_{y\mid \eta^{T}x},
\]

where **F** denotes the appropriate [distribution function](/Cumulative_distribution_function).  Another way to express this property is  

\[
y \perp\!\!\!\perp {\textbf x}\mid \eta^{T}{\textbf x},
\]

or **y** is [conditionally independent](/Conditional_independence) of **x**, given  

\[
\eta^{T}{\textbf x}
\].

Then the subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}(\eta)
\]

is defined to be a dimension reduction subspace (DRS) . [2]  

## Structural dimensionality

For a regression  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

, the structural dimension ,  

\[
d
\]

, is the smallest number of distinct linear combinations of **x** necessary to preserve the conditional distribution of  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\].  

In other words, the smallest dimension reduction that is still sufficient maps **x** to a subset of  

\[
\mathbb{R}^{d}
\].  

The corresponding DRS will be *d*‑dimensional. [2]  

## Minimum dimension reduction subspace

A subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}
\]

is said to be a minimum DRS for  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

if it is a DRS and its dimension is less than or equal to that of all other DRSs for  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\].  

A minimum DRS  

\[
\mathcal{S}
\]

is not necessarily unique, but its dimension is equal to the structural dimension  

\[
d
\]

of  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

, by definition. [2]  

If  

\[
\mathcal{S}
\]

has basis  

\[
\eta
\]

and is a minimum DRS, then a plot of **y** versus  

\[
\eta^{T}{\textbf x}
\]

is a minimal sufficient summary plot , and it is (*d* + 1)‑dimensional.  

## Central subspace

If a subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}
\]

is a DRS for  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

, and if  

\[
\mathcal{S} \subset \mathcal{S}_{\text{drs}}
\]

for all other DRSs  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{\text{drs}}
\],

then it is a central dimension reduction subspace , or simply a central subspace , and it is denoted by  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}
\].

In other words, a central subspace for  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

exists [if and only if](/If_and_only_if) the intersection  

\[
\bigcap \mathcal{S}_{\text{drs}}
\]

of all dimension reduction subspaces is also a dimension reduction subspace, and that intersection is the central subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}
\].  

[2]  

The central subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}
\]

does not necessarily exist because the intersection  

\[
\bigcap \mathcal{S}_{\text{drs}}
\]

is not necessarily a DRS.  However, if  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}
\]

does exist, then it is also the unique minimum dimension reduction subspace.  

## Existence of the central subspace

While the existence of the central subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}
\]

is not guaranteed in every regression situation, there are some rather broad conditions under which its existence follows directly.  For example, consider the following proposition from Cook (1998):

Let  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{1}
\]

and  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{2}
\]

be dimension reduction subspaces for  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\].

If **x** has [density](/Probability_density_function)

\[
f(a)>0
\]

for all  

\[
a\in\Omega_{x}
\]

and  

\[
f(a)=0
\]

everywhere else, where  

\[
\Omega_{x}
\]

is [convex](/Convex_set), then the intersection  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{1}\cap\mathcal{S}_{2}
\]

is also a dimension reduction subspace.

It follows from this proposition that the central subspace  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}
\]

exists for such **x**. [2]  

## Methods for dimension reduction

There are many existing methods for dimension reduction, both graphical and numeric.  For example, [sliced inverse regression](/Sliced_inverse_regression) (SIR) and sliced average variance estimation (SAVE) were introduced in the 1990s and continue to be widely used. [3]  Although SIR was originally designed to estimate an effective dimension [reducing subspace] , it is now understood that it estimates only the central subspace, which is generally different.  

More recent methods for dimension reduction include [likelihood](/Likelihood_function)-based sufficient dimension reduction, [4] estimating the central subspace based on the inverse third [moment](/Moment_(mathematics)) (or *k*‑th moment), [5] estimating the central solution space, [6] graphical regression, [2] envelope model, and the principal [support vector machine](/Support_vector_machine). [7]  For more details on these and other methods, consult the statistical literature.  

[Principal components analysis](/Principal_components_analysis) (PCA) and similar methods for dimension reduction are not based on the sufficiency principle.  

## Example: linear regression

Consider the regression model  

\[
y = \alpha + \beta^{T}{\textbf x} + \varepsilon ,
\]

where  

\[
\varepsilon \perp\!\!\!\perp {\textbf x}.
\]

Note that the distribution of  

\[
y\mid {\textbf x}
\]

is the same as the distribution of  

\[
y\mid \beta^{T}{\textbf x}.
\]

Hence, the span of  

\[
\beta
\]

is a dimension reduction subspace.  Also,

\[
\beta^{T}{\textbf x}
\]

is 1‑dimensional (unless  

\[
\beta = 0
\]),

so the structural dimension of this regression is  

\[
d = 1.
\]

The [OLS](/Ordinary_least_squares) estimate  

\[
\hat{\beta}
\]

of  

\[
\beta
\]

is [consistent](/Consistent_estimator), and so the span of  

\[
\hat{\beta}
\]

is a consistent estimator of  

\[
\mathcal{S}_{y\mid x}.
\]

The plot of **y** versus  

\[
\hat{\beta}^{T}{\textbf x}
\]

is a sufficient summary plot for this regression.  

